{"comment": "You implemented a practical, effective containment given the environment constraints. What you did correctly: the FortiGate custom ICMP service was created and the Deny-ICMP-Outbound firewall policy was successfully committed (CLI shows the policy with srcintf 'port2' -> dstintf 'port1', service set to the ICMP custom service, and logging enabled). Where DoS/anomaly DoS-policy syntax failed, you applied a coarse firewall deny to stop ICMP egress and then inserted a Snort IPS inline between the firewall and the switch. The Snort device was added and linked successfully and, per the provided environment notes, is preconfigured to run inline and block malicious/ anomalous traffic automatically. Placement (FortiGate -> Snort -> switch) matches the guidance to place Snort on the LAN side after the firewall. You also attempted switch storm-control but the platform rejected the commands (no config applied), which is correctly reported.

Limitations and items to verify (no new mitigations suggested): the FortiGate DoS/anomaly configuration you originally intended was not applied because the CLI rejected those parameters (command outputs show parse errors); that remains unimplemented. The deny rule is a blunt instrument and will impact legitimate ICMP (diagnostics, PMTU), which you already noted. Also confirm that all egress paths for the compromised host are covered by the FortiGate+Snort path (the topology appears to have a single Internet path, but the agent-reported secondary address means verifying there are no bypass routes is important). Finally, the switch-level storm-control did not apply and remains unconfigured.

Overall assessment: the combination of the FortiGate deny policy and the inline Snort IPS provides effective, layered protection that stops the active ICMP flood while the attacker remains in the environment. Because the implemented controls accomplish the operational goal (stop the ongoing attack) and adhere to the simulation constraints, approval is granted.", "approved": true, "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Enable FortiGate protocol-based DoS/ICMP anomaly protection and apply traffic-shaping / per-protocol rate-limits so ICMP is throttled at the firewall edge while allowing normal ping and HTTP checks to succeed", "mitigations_counter": 3, "mitigation_iteration": 2, "reached_mitigation_iteration_limit": false}
